Basically each module has default imports that it draws from where it's imported.

On a related note - something that came up the other day in chatting with another Rust dev: you can't easily replace a dependency one of your dependencies use. This means as your project grows...

tweet:
These days Code is 94% TS (according to gh), but that didn't happen all at once. Once devs found they preferred TS more, the change came naturally.

My hope with @nu_shell is that it will let folks try it for different things, and if it sticks, adoption will happen naturally.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: When we first started on @typescript, rather than asking teams to rewrite from their vanilla JS codebases, we gave ways to bridge what they had to TS. Lower risk, so more devs gave it a try. The early @code codebase was all JS. Later, bit by bit it moved to TS.

description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:

I'm a big believer that technology adoption is best when incremental, growing just from people trying it and preferring it.

tweet: It's fascinating to me that competition can push people to think outside of the box and come up with sustainable, competition-level techniques on a game about to celebrate its 32nd year.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Just the ergonomics of pushing buttons quickly meant risking injury.

And then... some players got really, really clever.

I'll let you watch the video about this new third way of moving.

https://t.co/9nCHFCvIOo

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
The result is that not only did they get passed level 29, it wasn't surprising to see pros fighting it out to level 30 or beyond in competition play.

It seemed like this would be the physical limitation, though. Sure you can hyper tap, but there's a limit, right?

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Then the maxout became an expected for any high-level tetris player. The "kill screen" was similar. At level 29, it was believed the pieces fell so fast that it was impossible to play into this level.

Then came "hyper-tapping" where players used fast motions to press buttons.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
A ğŸ§µof me nerding out on NES tetris.

The last ten years has seen some pretty amazing changes in high-level tetris play. It seemed like nearly each year, the top level pros pushed each other harder and harder. At first, getting to a maxout (999999 points) was an achievement.

tweet:
It's a cool feature, but I haven't made up my mind on if I like it or not. Giving that a bit more time to see if it becomes a natural part of my workflow.

To recap: NixOS is pretty rad, especially if you want more fine-grained control, albeit at a bit of extra config costs.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: One particular quirk I'm still getting used to: as a developer you often use something that's like an environment overlay but a bit more powerful (you can read about these looking for 'nix-shell') This also lets you control which dev packages are visible.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Just reboot and pick the previous configuration and you're back where you were. The unused packages can be gc'd, so they don't take up extra space.

The end result feels like a much more precisely configured install than you might have with more general audience distros.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: The purely functional thing comes in handy because it means that you can rollback effortlessly to a previous install. I've been using it maybe 10 days (?) so far and I've already gone down one configuration path I immediately regretted. No problem!

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: The idea is relatively simple: think of your package system like a pure functional data structure. You install packages, and basically build a "snapshot" of configuration for a point in time. This config you describe in a file, which makes it easy to reuse (reinstall/new install)

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:

tweet:
Conclusion: stick with native data types and box whole vectors where possible, rather than one-size-fits-all internal data representations.

I filling out the full picture a piece at a time. It's fun to experiment and see where changes would make a big difference.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Tonight I was looking at our big int data type and comparing it with a native i64. 

BigInt: 225.58ms
i64: 31.03ms

Same idea as above: sum a million values. The i64 one is also doing some extra work checking for overflow and switching to big int when it's detected.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
For comparison, Python does `sum(range(1, 1000001)) in 0.027 secs for me, so roughly 40x faster.

Conclusion: let's hold data in its natural representation for as long as possible. Don't expand a range only to have to process each row separately. Send the range as a single value.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
For example, in Nu you can do:

> echo 1..1000000 | math sum

And sum all the numbers from 1 to 1000000. The problem is that this is outputting a million rows through the pipeline, then `math sum` is having to .await() each one on the other end.

Total time: 1.025 secs

Seeing Tom Holland slay in something I would have liked to dance in, I feel this sadness for this kid, who learned too young and too deeply how dangerous it is to stand out.

It also makes me feel all this hope about what kids now and in the future will be allowed to do.

description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
It worked, they ran away, but in the back of my mind I could still hear that bullied kid say "see, that's what happens when you put yourself out there, people will try to hurt you".

I'm 42 now, and that bullied kid is still in there warning me.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Later in life, as I got more comfortable, I went dancing with a girlfriend. We were both dressed up, I was in a blouse. I liked them when dancing.

A group of guys came up and started commenting on what I was wearing, and my date, to her credit, snapped at them.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
It wasn't until I got to college that I started to understand a side of me that was impossible to see in a very religious house. There definitely was something a bit queer there.

Fast forward a few years, and I start explore that side more, though still unsure of what's going on

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
This went on for months. I somehow managed to keep it together until high school the following year, when things thankfully cooled off and I could meet some new people.

Back then, I thought I was straight as an arrow. What in the world were they talking about?

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: If there's anything that puts a target on your back in rural Virginia in 1991, it was being called gay. Overnight I became a pariah, and multiple bullies took an interest in me. Nearly everyday something would happen. Getting hit when the teacher wasn't looking, called names, etc

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: I couldn't have been more wrong. When I arrived, the school year was already half over, so I tried to make friends. I met a girl who took an interest in me. After a few days of calling me, I told her I wasn't interested in "that way". Just like that, rumors started.

Having the right frame of mind then becomes crucially important because of our on-going effect on the system we are part of.

In Buddhism, meditation is a tool to help both see this interconnectedness more clearly and act in a way that follows this understanding.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: Reminds me of the "butterfly effect" where changes to the way we see the world change our behavior, and in turn as our behavior changes they have a knock-on effect on those around us and so on.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
Understanding this interconnectedness runs throughout Buddhist philosophy.

The concept of "no self" might be more easily understood as "there is no separate, static self". Our self is always part of the system, and it's also always changing.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
One idea is "dependent origination". So far, I've been understanding this as "everything is part of the system". Nothing exists separate from the system.

The same for time: nothing is static in time.

We could say it as "everything is interconnected and ever-changing"

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
The Microsoft of today is even further along that path. You can see it in the GitHub stats, in how many tools are open source, in the way the C# team does design in the open, etc.

You hear that it's hard for bigco's to change, but it's impressive to me how fast things changed.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: Just after I left in 2015, one of my colleagues reached out to me and said "they've changed the default". It was no longer "why should this developer tool be OSS?" It was "why *shouldn't* it be?"  Microsoft was embracing open source more broadly and deeply with each month.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
I knew we didn't have all the answers, but I also knew that as more of Microsoft picked up this way of doing development, to connect what we did with the open source world where they were, things would grow.

It became easier and easier for teams to go OSS.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: Soon, myself, @ahejlsberg, and others were going and meeting with one team after another. The .NET team wanted to go OSS, various web projects... you name it. For a while there I was meeting with a team a week (or more) to share what we were learning doing TypeScript.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
With the change to GitHub, TypeScript really started taking off. Out of the gate, we had 10x the number of developers looking at us, then more. We went from being that project people had maybe heard of to filling rooms. 

This didn't go unnoticed. Other teams came to us.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: The worked paid off. Slowly but surely new policies replaced older policies. Another year later and @lukehoban, @amandaksilver, and others had met with enough of the leadership to move us finally onto GitHub.  Something clicked. What used to be uphill, started changing.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet: We went public, on CodePlex, and started building a small following. It was exciting. I was busy working with lawyers to let other teams use TypeScript (back then, source was very locked down and no one wanted to use something that could negatively impact releases)

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
So it began, we started the preparations for going public. First choice is where to put the source. At the time, MS had a service called CodePlex. It, literally, was under a desk somewhere.

We tried, and ultimately failed to move to GitHub.  CodePlex it was, at least it was OSS.

name: JT
description: Language nerd. @rustlang core team. @nu_shell co-creator. Prev: @typescript core team. ğŸŒˆ. ğŸ¶nerd.  #ActuallyAutistic. (they/them)
tweet:
@satyanadella was presented with the plan for TypeScript: let's take it open source, where the developers are, and grow a community with it.  It was a small project, but it had some potential.

Satya, to his credit (I was told, I wasn't there), was well-aware and supportive.
